Basic data analysis using R Studio

Anoop Ambikan

Introduction

This is a tutorial for performing basic data analysis using R studio. The tutorial cover basic statistical analysis including various pair-wise statistical tests, clustering and few basic data visualizations. Given below the topics covered in this tutorial.

  1. PCA
  2. UMAP
  3. statistical tests for 2 groups
  4. statistical tests for >2 groups
  5. Box and violin plots
  6. Bar graphs
  7. Limma
  8. Deseq2
  9. Piano

Package installation

A package is a bundle created using R programming language contains various functions perform specific tasks, demo data and user manuals. Developers create packages and make it publicly available for others to use. Developers submit the package in one of the repositories such as github, CRAN, Bioconductor or other private databases. We need to download source code for the package of interest and install locally to use it. Most of the packages can be installed by using the function install.packages(package name). The package name is case sensitive, we need to give the exact package name. There are specific functions to install packages from bioconductor and github.

Example installation 1

Open a new R script and save it as shown below.



Then check the package is already installed or not. It can be done by importing the package to rstudio using the command library(packageName). Type the command and hit Ctrl + Enter . If not installed, it will say package not available



If not installed, search for the package to find if it is available in CRAN (look for the URL)



If it is available in CRAN type the below command and hit Ctrl + Enter



Check for successful installation. It will show DONE . Sometime it will show errors like, dependency packages are not available



Some package needs other package pre-installed. In that case install those first and then install the package of interest .



Example installation 2

If the package is part of Bioconductor. Go to the bioconductor page.



copy the command for installation



We need to have pre-installed BiocManager package to install package from Bioconductor. So first install that



Execute command for installing PCA tools



PCA

Firstly, for easy use, you can make a specific folder only for R and keep all the files inside. This can be done by the command setwd() meaning set working directory. Create a folder somewhere.



copy the path to the folder

copy paste the commands one by one and hit Ctrl+ Enter to execute. You dont need to copy the message written after #. That is just comment. not part of command



When giving file path from Windows, you need to change all \ to / . Once you set a folder as ur working directory it will remain like that till you close the R script. All the input files should be there in the folder and outputs will be written to there as well. 

setwd("/home/anoop/Desktop/Tutorial/Analysis/")  ## Set working directory (folder). Give ur own folder.

library(PCAtools)    # load the package

data=read.delim("Input_PCA.txt",row.names = 1)   # Column should be samples and row should be features (protein etc)
head(data)   # display the loaded data
meta=read.delim("Design.txt",row.names = 1)
p <- pca(data, metadata = meta, removeVar = 0.1)
head(p$variance)   # variance captured by each PCs

p$rotated$Group=meta$Group
write.table(p$rotated,file="PCA_results.txt",sep="\t",col.names = NA,quote = FALSE)  # Download the PCs of all samples and add the metadata to draw nicer plot using ggplot2

Dat=read.delim("PCA_results.txt",row.names = 1)

pdf("PCA_plot.pdf")
ggplot(Dat, aes(x=PC1, y=PC2,color=Group)) + geom_point(size=3.7,aes(fill=Group),shape=21)+
  scale_color_manual(values=c(HC="#335b76",anti_pos="#9eb4cc",mild="#ccac00",severe="#cc8400"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c(HC="#48690E",anti_pos="#C6E2FF",mild="#ffd700",severe="#ffa500"))+
  labs(x="PC1, 47.4% variance",y="PC2, 7.73% variance")+theme(axis.title = element_text(size=10),legend.position = c(0.87, 0.11),plot.margin = margin(1,1,1,1, "cm"),
                                                              legend.title=element_text(size=9),legend.text=element_text(size=7),legend.key.size = unit(0.5, "cm"))+
  guides(shape = guide_legend(nrow = 1)) 
dev.off()

## You can play with plot margin to control figure size
## Below is the command for PCA plot with ellipse and centroid

dat=read.delim("PCA_results.txt",row.names = 1)
gg <- merge(dat,aggregate(cbind(mean.pc1=PC1,mean.pc2=PC2)~Group,dat,mean),by="Group")
pdf("PCA_plot_with_Ellipse.pdf")
ggplot(gg, aes(PC1,PC2,color=Group))+geom_point(size=3,aes(fill=Group))+
  geom_point(aes(x=mean.pc1,y=mean.pc2),size=5)+
  geom_segment(aes(x=mean.pc1, y=mean.pc2, xend=PC1, yend=PC2))+
  scale_color_manual(values=c(HC="#335b76",anti_pos="#9eb4cc",mild="#ccac00",severe="#cc8400"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c(HC="#48690E",anti_pos="#C6E2FF",mild="#ffd700",severe="#ffa500"))+
  labs(x="PC1, 47.4% variance",y="PC2, 7.73% variance")+theme(axis.title = element_text(size=10),legend.position = c(0.87, 0.11),plot.margin = margin(1,1,1,1, "cm"),
                                                              legend.title=element_text(size=9),legend.text=element_text(size=7),legend.key.size = unit(0.5, "cm"))+
  guides(shape = guide_legend(nrow = 1))+
  stat_ellipse(geom = "polygon",aes(fill = Group), alpha = 0.15,linetype = "dotted")
dev.off()

statistical tests for 2 groups

library(tidyverse)
library(rstatix)

data=read.delim("Input_test.txt")  # Column should be features and row should be analysis groups
mydata <- data %>% as_tibble()

mydata.long <- mydata %>%
  pivot_longer(-Group, names_to = "variables", values_to = "value")

results <- mydata.long %>% group_by(variables) %>% t_test(value ~ Group) %>% adjust_pvalue(method = "BH") %>% add_significance()  ## t-test

write.table(as.data.frame(results),file="t_test_results.txt",sep = "\t",col.names = NA,quote = FALSE)

results <- mydata.long %>% group_by(variables) %>% wilcox_test(value ~ Group) %>% adjust_pvalue(method = "BH") %>% add_significance()  ## Mann-Whitney

write.table(as.data.frame(results),file="Mann_Whitney_results.txt",sep = "\t",col.names = NA,quote = FALSE)

statistical tests for >2 groups

library(tidyverse)
library(rstatix)

data=read.delim("Input_test.txt")  # Column should be features and row should be analysis groups
mydata <- data %>% as_tibble()

mydata.long <- mydata %>%
  pivot_longer(-Group, names_to = "variables", values_to = "value")

results <- mydata.long %>% group_by(variables) %>% anova_test(value ~ Group) %>% adjust_pvalue(method = "BH") %>% add_significance()  ## ANOVA

write.table(as.data.frame(results),file="Anova_results.txt",sep = "\t",col.names = NA,quote = FALSE)

results <- mydata.long %>% group_by(variables) %>% kruskal_test(value ~ Group) %>% adjust_pvalue(method = "BH") %>% add_significance()  ## kruskal-wallis rank sum test

write.table(as.data.frame(results),file="kruskal_test_results.txt",sep = "\t",col.names = NA,quote = FALSE)

5. Box and violin plots

Data=read.delim("Input_test.txt",header = TRUE,check.names = FALSE)
head(Data)
Selected=Data %>% select(2:11)
Selected$Group=Data$Group
head(Selected)

library(reshape2)
library(ggpubr)
library(ggplot2)

M=melt(Selected,id.vars = "Group")

my_comparisons = list( c("HC", "mild"),c("HC", "severe"),c("mild", "severe"))
pdf("BoxPlot.pdf",width = 15,height = 12)
ggplot(M,aes(x=factor(Group,levels = unique(Group)),y=value,fill=Group,color=Group))+
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)+
  facet_wrap(~ variable, ncol = 5,nrow = 2,scales ="free" )+
  geom_jitter(shape=16, size=1,color="black",position=position_jitter(0.05))+
  scale_color_manual(values=c(HC="#335b76",anti_pos="#9eb4cc",mild="#ccac00",severe="#cc8400"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c(HC="#48690E",anti_pos="#C6E2FF",mild="#ffd700",severe="#ffa500"))+
  theme_bw()+
  stat_compare_means(label = "p.format",comparisons = my_comparisons,method = "wilcox.test")+
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),axis.title.y = element_blank(),legend.position ="right",panel.border = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),axis.text.x = element_blank(),legend.title = element_blank(),legend.text = element_text(size = 15),
        plot.margin = margin(4,0.1,4,0.1, "cm"),strip.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.text.y = element_text(color="black",size=12),plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,size = 15))+
  guides(color = guide_legend(ncol = 1),fill = guide_legend(ncol = 1))
dev.off()

        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),axis.text.x = element_blank(),legend.title = element_blank(),legend.text = element_text(size = 15),
